          </p>

          <p>
            This guide explains how time differences between countries really
            work and how you can calculate them accurately every time.
          </p>
        </section>

        <!-- WHAT IS -->
        <section id="what-is">
          <h2>What Is the Time Difference Between Countries?</h2>

          <p>
            The time difference between countries refers to the number of hours
            and minutes separating their local times. This difference exists
            because the Earth is divided into multiple time zones.
          </p>

          <p>
            Each time zone is defined as an offset from Coordinated Universal
            Time (UTC). For example, India follows UTC+5:30, while Japan follows
            UTC+9.
          </p>
        </section>

        <!-- WHY CHANGES -->
        <section id="why-changes">
          <h2>Why Time Difference Is Not Always Constant</h2>

          <p>
            Many people assume that the time difference between two countries
            never changes. In reality, it can shift several times a year.
          </p>

          <p>
            This happens because some countries observe daylight saving time
            while others do not. When one country moves its clocks and the other
            stays the same, the time difference changes.
          </p>
        </section>

        <!-- DST -->
        <section id="dst-impact">
          <h2>How Daylight Saving Time Affects Time Difference</h2>

          <p>
            Daylight Saving Time (DST) temporarily shifts local time forward or
            backward, usually by one hour. Different countries start and end
            DST on different dates.
          </p>

          <p>
            As a result, the time difference between two countries can change
            even if neither country has officially changed its standard time
            zone.
          </p>

          <p>
            This is why DST-aware tools are critical for accurate calculations.
            Learn more in our guide on
            <a href="/blog/daylight-saving-time-explained/">
              daylight saving time
            </a>.
          </p>
        </section>

        <!-- HOW TO CALC -->
        <section id="how-to-calc">
          <h2>How to Calculate Time Difference Between Countries</h2>

          <p>
            The most reliable method is to compare both countries using UTC as
            the reference point.
          </p>

          <ul>
            <li>Find each country’s current UTC offset</li>
            <li>Account for daylight saving time if applicable</li>
            <li>Subtract one offset from the other</li>
          </ul>

          <p>
            Instead of doing this manually, using a
            <a href="/time-difference/">Time Difference & Work Hours</a>
            tool ensures accuracy and saves time.
          </p>
        </section>

        <!-- COMMON MISTAKES -->
        <section id="common-mistakes">
          <h2>Common Mistakes People Make</h2>

          <p>
            Time difference errors often come from assumptions and outdated
            information.
          </p>

          <ul>
            <li>Assuming time difference never changes</li>
            <li>Ignoring daylight saving time</li>
            <li>Using country-level time for multi-zone countries</li>
            <li>Relying on memory instead of tools</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

